<br>
As I picked up his limp, lifeless body from the ground, his black fur glistening in the June sun, I did something I do perhaps once a year. I cried, there, in the street, for a lost friend.<br>
<br>
Now, I have owned many cats and dogs over the years, and as a child. However, I have never had a cat like Merry. He was truly unique. He did not meow obsessively at night, nor did he claw up the furniture. He didn't fight with the dog, or stubbornly refuse to be house-trained. He was the best you could hope for in a cat.<br>
<br>
I have fond memories of coming home, and seeing him asleep on the living room chair. He had his favorite white pillow beside him and, curled up into a tiny black ball with his eyes closed, seemed far away in a dreamland bliss. He was something you could look at, and say, &quot;I wish I could feel that content, if only for a minute.&quot; Other times, he would stand up on the computer table like <a href="http://www3.sympatico.ca/palad/cat.jpg">in this picture</a>, and just stare at me with those silvery-yellow eyes. <br>
<br>
If he needed something, he would let you know by meowing beside you. He would talk to you. If you said, &quot;Treats for Merry!&quot; beside the fridge, he'd run to you in anticipation of a small slice of cheese, or a piece of ham. His world was in that moment, the anticipation of that single piece of food, and once he got it, he was in complete rapture.<br>
<br>
He had no friend quite like my dog Tessa, though. Tessa is a border collie, and the two of them would play in the backyard during the day. Watching the rough dog learn to play with the precision-minded, gentle cat was quite a sight. Since his friend was there, Merry would not leave the yard, and when tired of playing with the dog, was content to sit on the step to watch the robins on the front lawn in the morning, and meow at the door to come in at the end of the day.<br>
<br>
Now, in my closet I have two bags of cat food, a litter box, and a bag of cat treats. I have two broken slices of cheese in the fridge which were his treats, and his nylon collar on my dresser. The ragdoll-like cat with the soft, black fur now sleeps in the backyard, under a neat cross with my sister's writing on it, which reads:<br>
<br>
Merry <br>
We miss you<br>
Dear friend<br>
<br>
He was not merely a pet, he was a friend. He was a staple in our lives, painfully ripped from our hearts in a brief moment of fury and blood, and a faint cry of pain. Back to the earth, in our backyard, in this quiet rural Quebec town, he sleeps beneath weeping willows and a silver maple.<br>
<br>
So long, friend, you will be missed.<br>
